body:
# MongoDB Transactions

Use transactions only when a single-document atomic write is not enough. They are powerful, but they add coordination cost and require a topology that supports them.

## withTransaction Example

```javascript
const session = client.startSession();

await session.withTransaction(async () => {
  const db = client.db("bank");
  await db.collection("checking_accounts").updateOne(
    { account_id: "9876" },
    { $inc: { amount: -100 } },
    { session }
  );
  await db.collection("savings_accounts").updateOne(
    { account_id: "9876" },
    { $inc: { amount: 100 } },
    { session }
  );
}, {
  readPreference: "primary",
  readConcern: { level: "local" },
  writeConcern: { w: "majority" },
  maxCommitTimeMS: 1000
});
```

## Constraints That Matter

- Transactions require a replica set or sharded cluster, not a standalone `mongod`
- Do not run parallel operations inside the same transaction callback
- Expect retry-worthy transient errors and design the callback to be idempotent
- Prefer embedding related data when a single-document write can model the invariant

Use [[mongodb/crud]] first. Escalate to transactions only when the invariant truly spans multiple documents or collections.
